	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">runaway pancake wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I could just use a laptop if all I wanted to do was play NES games on a TV  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>
<br />You could, but others might not:
<br /><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>Not many people are aware that PCs can display on TVs. They aren't aware that DVI out connects to HDMI in, that a lot of North American HDTVs have a VGA input (which European TVs often give up for SCART), or that SewellDirect.com sells a $30 cable to turn a VGA signal into a PAL or NTSC composite signal for an SDTV. In the mind of the general public, TVs are for living rooms and PCs are for desks and never the twain shall meet. </li><li>There tends to be a lot more controller-to-video and controller-to-audio latency in PC-based emulation than there is on an NES. I once measured 100 ms for VisualBoyAdvance on Windows, which made rhythm games unplayable. A single-tasking embedded system could shave tens of milliseconds off this. </li></ol>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


